{#- LLM-facing text is English-only: Cyrillic uses roughly 2–3× more tokens per word.
    This Jinja comment is stripped and never sent to the model.
    docs/ARCHITECTURE.md §6.2: tool-spec for route `logic_validate`. -#}
{
  "type": "function",
  "function": {
    "name": "logic_validate",
    "description": "Formal logic-verification engine: check whether your facts satisfy a set of rules and get back every rule that is violated. Use it to PROVE your own reasoning before asserting it — not to look up facts (that is memory_query).\n\nWhen to use:\n- You derived a conclusion from several premises ('if A and B then C') and have not proven the step.\n- You must enforce a domain invariant (ordering, cardinality, type, range, mutual exclusion) on facts you constructed.\n- You suspect a contradiction or inconsistency and must confirm it before acting.\n- You are about to finalize a non-trivial logical claim and want it provably correct, not merely plausible.\n\nWhen NOT to use: to retrieve a fact, value, or saved note → memory_query; for a trivial claim already supported by <knowledge_graph>/<thread_memory>/<global_memory> → finalize directly; for SHACL/Turtle syntax help alone → memory_query the reference instead.\n\nMental model: shapes_ttl is your suite of 'tests' (SHACL shapes; arbitrary first-order predicates go in SHACL-SPARQL sh:sparql), facts_ttl is the 'state under test' (RDF/Turtle). The pySHACL engine evaluates the rules and reports conformance.\n\nTwo semantics decide whether the result is meaningful:\n1. In sh:sparql the SELECT/WHERE must match the VIOLATING case — the NEGATION of your invariant. Every returned row is reported as a violation. To check 'end >= start', FILTER for the bad case (?end < ?start), not the good one.\n2. conforms=true is NOT positive proof: if a shape's target matches nothing (typo in a class/prefix, or inference you did not enable), the check is vacuous and still says conforms=true — the observation warns you. Never treat a vacuous pass as a proof.\n\nPrefixes used inside sh:select do NOT inherit the document's @prefix lines; declare each via sh:prefixes/sh:declare (and @prefix xsd: for the ^^xsd:anyURI namespace literal) or the query fails at runtime.\n\nReturns: conforms (true/false) + violation count + a report naming each failed rule (plus a vacuous-target warning when applicable). Idempotent, no side effects. Read the report carefully before retrying.\n\nFor the full Turtle/SHACL/SPARQL reference and more worked examples, memory_query the knowledge base: turtle_syntax.md, shacl_sparql.md, sparql_functions.md.\n\nMinimal example (FILTER selects the violation; note the explicit sh:prefixes):\n```turtle\n@prefix sh: <http://www.w3.org/ns/shacl#> .\n@prefix xsd: <http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#> .\n@prefix ex: <http://example.org/> .\n\nex:TimeOrderShape a sh:NodeShape ;\n  sh:targetClass ex:Event ;\n  sh:sparql [\n    sh:prefixes [ sh:declare [ sh:prefix \"ex\" ; sh:namespace \"http://example.org/\"^^xsd:anyURI ] ] ;\n    sh:select \"\"\"\n      SELECT $this (ex:endDate AS ?path) (?end AS ?value)\n      WHERE { $this ex:startDate ?start ; ex:endDate ?end . FILTER (?end < ?start) }\n    \"\"\" ;\n    sh:message \"Event end must not precede start\" ;\n  ] .\n```",
    "parameters": {
      "type": "object",
      "properties": {
        "shapes_ttl": {
          "type": "string",
          "minLength": 1,
          "maxLength": 32000,
          "description": "SHACL shapes graph (your logical assertions/constraints) in Turtle. Each shape encodes an invariant or rule that the data must satisfy. Use sh:sparql for complex predicates (the WHERE clause must select VIOLATING nodes). Declare prefixes used inside sh:select via sh:prefixes/sh:declare. Must include @prefix sh: <http://www.w3.org/ns/shacl#> (and @prefix xsd: when you use ^^xsd:anyURI)."
        },
        "facts_ttl": {
          "type": "string",
          "minLength": 1,
          "maxLength": 32000,
          "description": "Data graph (the facts/conclusions you want to verify) in Turtle. This is 'the state under test' — encode your derived relationships, inferred facts, or proposed domain state here."
        },
        "ontology_ttl": {
          "type": "string",
          "maxLength": 32000,
          "description": "Optional ontology graph (rdfs:subClassOf, owl:equivalentClass, property domains/ranges) merged into the facts. sh:targetClass already follows rdfs:subClassOf when selecting targets without any inference. Full RDFS/OWL entailment — rdfs:domain/range type inference, owl:equivalentClass, property hierarchies — only takes effect if you also set the `inference` parameter."
        },
        "inference": {
          "type": "string",
          "enum": ["none", "rdfs", "owlrl", "both"],
          "description": "Optional RDFS/OWL reasoning to run before validation. Default 'none'. Required for owl:equivalentClass, rdfs:domain/range type inference, and property-hierarchy entailment to fire; plain subclass-based sh:targetClass works without it. 'owlrl'/'both' are more expensive — use only when your rules depend on that entailment."
        },
        "reasoning": {
          "type": "string",
          "minLength": 1,
          "maxLength": 2000,
          "description": "What logical property you are verifying and why — short text for logs and the observation note."
        }
      },
      "required": ["shapes_ttl", "facts_ttl", "reasoning"],
      "additionalProperties": false
    }
  }
}
